SIMPLE: sublimation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sublimation
<hw>Sub"li*ma`tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>sublimatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>sublimation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The act or process of subliming, or the state or
result of being sublimed.</def> <-- the process of vaporizing a solid
and recondensing it into a solid, without it having first passed into
the liquid state. Certain solids, such as camphor, have a suffiently
high vapor pressure in the solid phase to make this a practical method
for purification. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of heightening or improving; exaltation;
elevation; purification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is sublimed; the product of a purifying
process.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Religion is the perfection, refinement, and <qex>sublimation</qex>
of morality.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sublimatory</ent>⟦br⟧
